				\begin{document}$m=\underset {\gamma \in \{1,2,3,4\}}{\arg \max } \text {} P(\gamma |\mathbf {y}^{g}, \mathbf {n}^{g})$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M176"><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:munder><mml:mrow><mml:mo>arg</mml:mo><mml:mo>max</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>γ</mml:mi><mml:mo>∈</mml:mo><mml:mo>{</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mn>2</mml:mn><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mn>3</mml:mn><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mn>4</mml:mn><mml:mo>}</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:munder><mml:mtext/><mml:mi>P</mml:mi><mml:mo>(</mml:mo><mml:mi>γ</mml:mi><mml:mo>|</mml:mo><mml:msup><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="bold">y</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>g</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msup><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msup><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="bold">n</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>g</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msup><mml:mo>)</mml:mo></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2019_3141_Article_IEq81.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> for <italic>g</italic>=1,…,<italic>G</italic>. Let <italic>P</italic>(<italic>g</italic>∈{<italic>m</italic>}|<bold>y</bold><sup><italic>g</italic></sup>,<bold>n</bold><sup><italic>g</italic></sup>) denote the posterior probability of gene <italic>g</italic> being sampled from Model <italic>m</italic>. The posterior probability of a gene exhibiting an ASE gene effect is <italic>P</italic>(<italic>g</italic>∈{2,4}|<bold>y</bold><sup><italic>g</italic></sup>,<bold>n</bold><sup><italic>g</italic></sup>). Similarly, the posterior probability of a gene exhibiting ASE variations across SNPs is <italic>P</italic>(<italic>g</italic>∈{3,4}|<bold>y</bold><sup><italic>g</italic></sup>,<bold>n</bold><sup><italic>g</italic></sup>). Finally, the posterior probability of a gene exhibiting an ASE gene effect and ASE variations across SNPs simultaneously is <italic>P</italic>(<italic>g</italic>∈{4}|<bold>y</bold><sup><italic>g</italic></sup>,<bold>n</bold><sup><italic>g</italic></sup>). We adopt the following method to control FDR that have been used in [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR74">74</xref>, <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR75">75</xref>]. To control the FDR when testing the ASE gene effect, we order <italic>P</italic>(<italic>g</italic>∈{2,4}|<bold>y</bold><sup><italic>g</italic></sup>,<bold>n</bold><sup><italic>g</italic></sup>), <italic>g</italic>=1,…,<italic>G</italic>, from largest to smallest. Let <italic>g</italic><sub>(1)</sub>,…,<italic>g</italic><sub>(<italic>G</italic>)</sub> be the ordered genes; then, we find the largest <italic>l</italic> such that <inline-formula id="IEq82"><alternatives><tex-math id="M177">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
